>>> Folks,
>>> =

>>> Still no answer yet to the puzzler as to why a loop antenna without a f=
errite is good for a crystal radio set, while it seems to be favored to add=
 the ferrite to a transistor radio.
>>> =

>>> --Kirk
>>> =

>>> PS.  The first patented (2nd filed) crystal radio set used a loop anten=
na:
>>> http://history-computer.com/Library/US836531.pdf
>>> Pickard worked for what became ATT.
>>> =

>>> In contrast, the first filed, but 2nd patented set originally used a ki=
nd of =93linear=94 antenna.
>>> http://www.jmargolin.com/history/837616.pdf
>>> Other versions of this use a loop antenna
>>> http://www.maintradingcompany.com/cart/THE-DUNWOODY-HIGH-PERFORMANCE-CR=
YSTAL-RADIO-KIT!!.305
>>> =

>>> (I=92m impressed that a US Army General, rather than an =93engineer=94,=
 was the first to develop the crystal radio =96at age 63!   Dunwoody was ac=
quainted with de Forest, who was trying to develop radio systems at the tim=
e.
>>> =

>>> This was the first =93practical=94 application of a semiconductor diode=
, which was not exactly a household word in 1906.
>>> =

>>> The notion of the usefulness of a semiconductor detector for radio was =
due to JC Bose, who filed a US patent in 1901, but which was only awarded i=
n 1904.   Bose is more famous today for the Higgs Boson =96 in that all =93=
bosons=94 are named after him.
>>> http://www.pat2pdf.org/patents/pat755840.pdf
>>> He was a physicist, not an =93engineer=94.
>>> =

>>> Another early radio detector developed by a physicist was the magnetic =
coherer of Rutherford (originally invented when he was a student in New Zea=
land ~ 1895).  Marconi took up this concept and made it reasonably practica=
l around 1902.
